  "text": "Django's migration squashing compliance system consists of several key components working together:\n\n## Squash Migration Generator\n**django/core/management/commands/squashmigrations.py** - The `Command.handle()` method (line 61) is the entry point that orchestrates the entire squash process. It:\n- Loads the migration graph from the current state\n- Identifies migrations to squash using `loader.graph.forwards_plan()`\n- Collects operations and dependencies from all migrations being squashed\n- Optimizes the operations using `MigrationOptimizer`\n- Creates a new Migration class with `replaces` attribute listing all squashed migrations\n- Writes the new squashed migration file using `MigrationWriter`\n\n## Replaced-Migrations Tracking\n**django/db/migrations/migration.py** - The `Migration` class (line 9) defines the `replaces` attribute (line 42), which is a list of migration names that a squashed migration replaces. When a migration is instantiated (line 62), this attribute is copied as an instance variable. This enables the migration system to track which migrations have been consolidated into a squashed migration.\n\n**django/db/migrations/loader.py** - The `MigrationLoader` class maintains replacement tracking through:\n- `replacements` dictionary that maps migration keys to migrations that have a `replaces` attribute\n- `replacements_progress` dictionary used during `replace_migration()` calls to detect circular replacement chains\n- `_resolve_replaced_migration_keys()` method (line 224) which recursively resolves all migrations that are being replaced, handling cases where squashed migrations themselves replace other squashed migrations\n\n## Dependency Graph Validation After Squashing\n**django/db/migrations/graph.py** - The `MigrationGraph` class provides critical validation:\n- `remove_replaced_nodes()` method (line 125) - Removes each replaced migration node from the graph and repoints all parent and child dependencies to reference the replacement migration instead, ensuring the graph remains connected\n- `remove_replacement_node()` method (line 161) - The inverse operation that removes a replacement node and remaps dependencies back to replaced nodes (used when a replacement migration cannot be used due to partial application)\n- `validate_consistency()` method (line 198) - Ensures no dummy (nonexistent) nodes remain in the migration graph after replacement processing\n- `ensure_not_cyclic()` method (line 271) - Validates the dependency graph for circular dependencies using depth-first search\n\n**django/db/migrations/loader.py** - The `build_graph()` method (line 274) orchestrates the entire graph construction process:\n1. Loads all migrations from disk\n2. Identifies migrations with `replaces` attributes and stores them in the `replacements` dictionary\n3. Adds all nodes to the migration graph\n4. Adds internal (same-app) dependencies\n5. Adds external (cross-app) dependencies using `add_internal_dependencies()` and `add_external_dependencies()`\n6. Processes replacements by calling `replace_migration()` for each replacement migration\n7. Validates consistency using `graph.validate_consistency()`\n8. Checks for circular dependencies using `graph.ensure_not_cyclic()`\n\nThe `replace_migration()` method (line 235) handles the core replacement logic:\n- Detects circular replacement chains and raises CommandError if found\n- Recursively processes nested squashed migrations (squashes of squashes)\n- Resolves all replaced migration keys\n- Determines if the squashed migration can be safely used based on the applied status of replaced migrations:\n  - Can be used if ALL replaced migrations are applied (squash is complete and can replace them)\n  - Can be used if NONE of the replaced migrations are applied (new installation, use squashed form)\n  - Cannot be used if SOME replaced migrations are applied (partial state, indicates incomplete deployment)\n\n## Squash Completeness Check\n**django/db/migrations/loader.py** - The `all_replaced_applied()` method (line 372) recursively checks whether all replaced migrations for a given squashed migration have been applied to the database. This is critical for determining:\n- Whether a squashed migration can be recorded as applied\n- Whether a dependency on a replaced migration can be satisfied by checking if its replacement has been applied\n\nThe `check_consistent_history()` method (line 344) validates that applied migrations have all their dependencies applied, with special handling for partially-applied squashed migrations using `all_replaced_applied()`.\n\n**django/db/migrations/executor.py** - The `check_replacements()` method (line 294) marks replacement migrations as applied in the migration recorder if:\n- The replacement migration itself is not yet recorded as applied\n- All migrations it replaces have been applied\n\nThis handles the case where a new squash migration is deployed after the individual migrations it replaces have already been applied on all instances.\n\nThe `record_migration()` method (line 268) specially handles recording replacement migrations by recursively recording each replaced migration in addition to the replacement itself.\n\n## Migration File Writing\n**django/db/migrations/writer.py** - The `MigrationWriter.as_string()` method (line 129) handles serialization of the `replaces` attribute into the generated migration file, including it in the Migration class definition.\n\n## Additional Components\n**django/core/management/commands/optimizemigration.py** - Can create replacement migrations when optimizing existing migrations by setting the `replaces` attribute to point to the original migration.\n\n**django/db/migrations/autodetector.py** - Contains helper method to extract numbers from squashed migration names (line 2061) for comparison and sorting purposes.\n\nTogether, these components ensure that Django's migration squashing feature maintains referential integrity of the dependency graph, tracks which original migrations have been consolidated, validates the complete state of the system, and ensures that squashed migrations can be safely used only when appropriate (either on fresh installs or when all replaced migrations have been fully applied)."
